Purnululu National Park, Western Australia
Purnululu National Park, in north east of Western Australia, is a UNESCO World
Heritage Site. It contains the Bungle Bungle range with its orange and grey striped
domes forming one of Australia's most visually striking landscapes.

Salt Plain near Curtin Springs, Northern Territory
Vast and surreal, this salt plain in Central Australia is an ever-changing landscape,
constantly evolving with the effects of the heat, rain and wind. The pale salt crust
is in stark contrast to the arid red earth that surrounds it.

The Kimberley, Western Australia
The Kimberley is located in the northern part of Western Australia. It is one
of the world's last true wilderness areas and the place to go for an authentic
outback adventure or to simply relax on Broom's breathtaking Cable Beach.

Daintree Rainforest, Far North Queensland
135 million years in the making, the Daintree Rainforest is as ethereal as it is
spectacular. It's Australia's largest and most significant rainforest reserve, home to a
diverse range of native plant and animal species.
